, recorded before 1175, who went to Scotland from Ramsey (Huntingdonshire)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ramsey","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Irish (Antrim): habitational name from Ramsey (Huntingdonshire, now part of Cambridgeshire), from Old English <i>hramsa</i> ‘wild garlic’ + <i>ēg</i> ‘island, low-lying land’. Alternatively, the name may also arise from Ramsey (Essex), probably from the same etymology as the Huntingdonshire placename. However, this is unlikely to be the source of the Scottish surname. This form of the surname is also common in Ireland, where it is probably in most if not all cases an altered form of Scottish   Ramsay  ."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Simon Ramsay II was born in 1150, in Edinburgh, Scotland as the son of Simon Ramsay I. He had at least 2 sons. He died in 1196, in Dalhousie, Midlothian, Scotland, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1150–1196":"1150–1196","1160–1238":"1160–1238","1190–1250":"1190–1250","1232–Male":"1232–Surnud","1190":"1190","1238":"1238","about 1190":"umbes 1190","after 1170":"pärast 1170","before 1165":"enne 1165","1232":"1232","1196":"1196","1250":"1250","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland",